`TestInjectOsloPolicyConfig_doesNotMutateInput` only covers the non-empty-path case (line 409: `"/etc/nova/policy.yaml"`). The godoc explicitly documents that when `policyFilePath` is empty, the function "returns the original config reference unchanged (no copy is made)" — but this reference-identity contract is untested. A future refactor that accidentally makes a copy for the empty-path case would silently break the documented semantics without any test failure.

Consider adding a test that asserts the reference-identity for the no-op case:

```go
func TestInjectOsloPolicyConfig_emptyPathReturnsOriginalReference(t *testing.T) {
    g := NewGomegaWithT(t)

    config := map[string]map[string]string{
        "DEFAULT": {"debug": "true"},
    }

    result := InjectOsloPolicyConfig(config, "")

    // Empty path must return the exact same map reference (documented no-copy contract).
    g.Expect(result).To(BeIdenticalTo(config))

    // Mutating result must therefore also mutate config (caller beware).
    result["mutated"] = map[string]string{"key": "val"}
    g.Expect(config).To(HaveKey("mutated"))
}
```

